@*<div class="textblock">
    TxDOT’s recommendation for downtown freeways and Interstate 45 North is the most influential recommendation for Houston’s freeways since the 1950s. 
TxDOT and its partners deserve credit for a bold plan to fully modernize downtown Houston freeways and enhance mobility.
However, review of the preliminary schematics reveals numerous points of concern which could compromise the ability of the new freeway system to meet current and future needs.
</div>*@

<div class="bold">Updates resulting from July 22 and September 4, 2015, meetings with TxDOT</div>


<div class="updateItem">I attended two meetings with TxDOT about the project, the first on July 22 which focused on this list, and a second on September 4 which was held for Tory Gattis of <a href="http://houstonstrategies.blogspot.com/">Houston Strategies</a>. Representatives from HNTB, the consulting firm developing the design, were also in attendance. Only some of the issues were addressed on Septmber 4, so the status of many issues below is from July 22 as noted with each individual item.</div>

<div class="updateItem">The current status of each issue is based on these meetings. <b>These statuses are preliminary until the next version of the plan is officially released</b>. There were numerous changes between the July 22 and September 4 meetings.</div>

<div class="updateItem">I appreciate TxDOT's and HNTB's willingness to take a close look at each individual issue and host the two meetings to provide updates on the status of the development of the design.</div>



@*<div class="textblock">
    Disclaimer:  
    The points of concern in this analysis are identified based on existing traffic patterns and bottlenecks, using a common-sense approach in terms of overall lanes and lane balance.
    TxDOT and its consultant (HNTB) almost use detailed projected traffic counts and computer modeling to develop the plan.
    The schematics used were downloaded from the project web site in April 2015.
</div>*@

@*<div class="textblock">
<div class="problem-solution">Comments on the removal of the Pierce Elevated</div>
    From the mobility perspective, it is undesirable to remove the Pierce Elevated. It is preferable to have multiple routes rather than a single route, and placing all traffic on the east downtown spine introduces a single point of failure for the entire system.
    Even with the realignment of I-45, the Pierce transportation corridor (sunken into a trench) could be valuable for managed lanes or to provide capacity for connecting traffic.
    <p>
    But the removal appears to be certain to remain in the plan and the removal should have benefits for new development, so I won't object and instead I'll focus on the concerns of the new plan, some of which are serious.
</p>
</div>*@

