<a name="45-north-main"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">Interstate 45 North of Downtown: Insufficient Lanes at North Main (Woodland Heights/Hollywood Cemetery)</div>

<div class="textblock">
    <div>
        From North Main to Loop 610 there is no right-of-way acquisition to appease the neighborhood group, even though the west side of the freeway has only low-grade commercial establishments and no homes.
This introduces a serious bottleneck where six northbound main lanes are reduced to four lanes at North Main. At evening rush hour, this will potentially cause a backup that will cascade into the downtown interchange complex.
    </div>


    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Six northbound lanes reduced to only four lanes at North Main</li>
        <li>All lanes narrowed to 11 feet</li>
        <li>The bottleneck is exacerbated by the lack of access to the northbound managed lanes (see next issue)</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Add at least one northbound main lane through the North Main intersection and all the way to Loop 610.</li>
        <li>Acquire a modest strip of right-of-way on the west side to accommodate the needed lane(s).</li>
        <li>Ideally there should also be a fifth southbound lane</li>
        <li>Have standard-width 12-foot-wide lanes</li>
    </ul>

        <div class="itemStatus">September 4 Status: Substantial improvements in this area, tentative design is probably the best it can be given the constraints</div>
    <div class="itemStatusText">
        This is very good news, fixing my second most serious design concern. 
        The plan as of Septeber 4 has ten regular lanes underneath North Main, and the ten regular lanes are maintained to Loop 610. The new plan also has eight regular lanes crossing over Loop 610 (the original plan had six). All lanes are 12 feet wide.
        This is done with no new right-of-way acquisition, only perhaps a very minor impact to the Exxon on the northwest corner at North Main.
        <p>
        For northbound traffic, the September 4 plan still showed a two-lane exit to North Main and a reduction to four main lanes. However, there is a new collector ramp from downtown, which serves as a long entrance ramp from downtown. 
        The collector lane merges into the regular lanes south of North Main, and these changes taken together should solve the problem of the North Main bottleneck to the greatest extent possible given the contraints.
        </p>
        <p>
        There are also other improvements in the tentative plan. On southwest side of the North Main intersection there is a roundabout-style design on the frontage road to address neighborhood concerns. New U-turns have been added on the north side of North Main and on both sides of Cottage Street.
            The Cavalcade Street intersection is being designed to handle trucks originating and terminating at the truck stop on Patton Street.
        </p>

        
    </div>


