<a name="288-access"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">SH 288: drastically reduced access to southbound main lanes from downtown, and poor access going northbound</div>
<div class="textblock">
    <div>
        This is rather shocking if you are in central downtown and need to get on the SH 288 main lanes southbound.
    </div>

    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>The US 59 southbound on-ramp at Webster (just south of I-45) no longer provides access to SH 288</li>
        <li>The currently existing access from Chenevert Street will be for toll-paying managed lanes traffic only</li>
        <li>There is <span class="bold">only ONE</span> entrance to the SH 288 southbound main lanes for all of downtown, and it is at the south end of Midtown and is only one lane.</li>
        <li>Northbound exit into downtown is on the far south end of Midtown. Traffic can connect into US 59 for more exits, but that contributes more traffic to US 59.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Add a southbound entrance ramp from Pierce Street to the connector going to SH 288 southbound</li>
        <li>Add an exit ramp from the SH 288 connector to I-45 north to either St. Joseph, Gray or Pease</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="itemStatus">September 2015 Preliminary Status: Minor adjustments only are expected</div>
    <div class="itemStatusText">
        HNTB says the traffic model shows that the single lane entrance from the south end of Midtown in sufficient for all traffic orginating in the downtown area. The ideas that I proposed above are not feasible.
        As of September, a minor adjustment is anticipated to improve the efficiency to the planned southbound entrance from Chenevert street.
        
        <p>
            I still have a remaining concern about northbound SH 288. To avoid the long distance on surface streets to the center of downtown, many northbound SH 288 vehicles will exit to US 59 and then take the US 59 exit to Gray Street or Dallas Street.

            The lanes from SH 288 merge into US 59 on the left side of the US 59 main lanes, and then vehicles trying to exit at Gray will have to cross over to the right side of the US 59 main lanes in a very short distance (1600 feet), likely contributing to traffic flow disruption.
        </p>
        <p>
          The easy answer to this problem is to start the US 59 northbound exit to Gray Street around Elgin and make it barrier separated so that SH 288 traffic cannot access the exit. This will require some more width for the barrier and a shoulder, but it looks like it can be made to fit.
        </p>
    </div>

