<a name="pierce"></a>
<div class="comment-heading">Comment: Removal of the Pierce Elevated</div>
<div class="textblock">

    <div>
    From the mobility perspective, it is undesirable to remove the Pierce Elevated. It is preferable to have multiple routes rather than a single route, and placing all traffic on the east downtown spine introduces a single point of failure for the entire system.
    <p>
        Even with the realignment of I-45, the Pierce transportation corridor (sunken into a trench) could be valuable and useful.
        With I-45 realigned, the Pierce corridor could be used for managed lanes or to provide certain connections which would be useful, for example Allen Parkway and Memorial to the Gulf Freeway and South Freeway.
    </p>
    But the removal appears to be certain to remain in the plan and the removal should have benefits for new development, so I won't object and instead I'll focus on the concerns of the new plan, some of which are serious.
    </div>

            <div class="itemStatus">July and Septmeber 2015 Preliminary Status: TxDOT wants to sell the Pierce Elevated land, and Pierce Elevated will not be used for transporation purposes</div>
    <div class="itemStatusText">
        This verifies what I said above in the original posting, which is that the Pierce Elevated corridor is definitely a goner for highway transportation purposes. TxDOT wants to sell the land and use to funds to buy expensive right-of-way which is needed for the
        wide trench on the east side of downtown. TxDOT is required to offer the land to the City of Houston first, then (assuming the City of Houston does not want it) it must offer the land to adjacent landowners, and only  then  could TxDOT
        sell the land to any buyers. (I'm assuming that the price for adjacent landowners would be set by an independent appraiser; prices to any buyer would be market price of course.) It is unclear to me what the price would be to the City of Houston, but TxDOT wants as much as possible. Of course TxDOT operates in a political environment, and political leaders could set
        a price to favor the City of Houston if in fact the city is interested. 
        <p>
            At the Septmber meeting, HNTB mentioned that land in that area is worth around $100 per square foot, and the net gain to TxDOT (after legal and professional fees) is expected to be around $65 per square foot. Of course, market prices
            fluctuate and could be much different by the time the land can actually be sold, and tracts on the west end would likly be much more valuable than land on the east side.
            

        </p>
        <p>
            The Pierce Elevated uses about 14 half-blocks. Each half-block is around 250 x 125 feet, or 31,250 square feet. At $100 per square foot, that works out to about $3.1 million per half block, or $43 million for the 14 half-blocks, with a net to TxDOT around $28 million.
            </P>
        <p>
            A $28 million net seems to be quite low in terms of the overall cost of the project, and makes a Pierce Elevated Park or Pierce Skypark a very realistic option, since I could see the City of Houston coming up with $28 million for a highly distinctive urban park.
            The proposed deck park over the trench on the east side of downtown will be vastly more expensive, at least $100 million just for the deck, and a total cost around $150 to $300 million, depending on the size and complexity of the park.

        </p>
    </div>
</div>
